Step 1 (upgrade): Replace the freeform formula with a signal spec contract
The hand-off artifact between ideation and implementation should be a fixed-schema spec file (YAML/MD), not prose. Minimum fields:

Inputs: exact tables/fields (must match data-card names)
Universe & frequency: which univ file, daily/intraday, region
PIT rule: which timestamp gates availability; explicit as-of lag (e.g., "usable at T+1 open, KRX flow published T 18:00 KST")
Formula: in pseudocode/math with every parameter pinned (lookback windows, winsorization, z-score cross-sectional vs. time-series, NA handling, min-coverage threshold)
Neutralization: none / market / industry / your existing risk factors
Hypothesis & expected sign, horizon, decay — written before running (this is your pre-registration; it's what protects the eval from becoming p-hacking)
Free parameters allowed to tune vs. frozen — declare in advance, cap the count

Opus's stage-1 role becomes a structured feasibility review of this spec against the data cards: field exists? PIT achievable? survivorship issues? corporate-action adjustment needed? suggested amendments returned as a spec diff, which you can round-trip to GPT/Fable verbatim. Once both sides sign off, the spec is frozen and versioned — Opus then implements only what's in the spec (your requirement #2), and any deviation it thinks necessary comes back as a proposed spec amendment, never a silent code decision.
Step 2 (upgrade): Smoke test → validation battery
One day locally is too weak. Replace with:

Golden examples: 3–5 stock-days hand-computed (or computed by Opus in a separate session from raw data) and asserted in unit tests.
Stratified sample days: a normal day, a crisis day, an index-rebalance/expiry day, a holiday-adjacent day, and a day near a known data-regime change (e.g., China northbound disclosure ending Aug 2024).
Automated lookahead tests: shift all input timestamps forward one day — signal values for day T must not change if PIT logic is correct; also assert no signal exists before each dataset's history start, and coverage counts look sane per day.
Distribution sanity: cross-sectional coverage, NA rate, autocorrelation/turnover of the term — compared against the spec's expectations.

Make this battery a fixed harness so Opus runs it identically for every idea.
Step 3 (upgrade): Full run into a standardized eval + registry
Every term, no exceptions, goes through the same evaluation report:

Rank-IC by horizon (1d/5d/10d/21d) with Newey-West t-stats, IC decay curve, long-short quantile returns, turnover and capacity proxy (ADV-weighted)
Residual IC after neutralizing your existing alpha stack — this is the number that matters for you, since the whole mandate is "not detected by current systematic approach." Raw IC is nearly irrelevant; report correlation to your existing composite and marginal contribution.
Subperiod stability (at minimum pre/post split, plus around known regime breaks per region)
Event-time CAR plots for event-type signals (most of your backlog — 减持, TOBs, Shariah revisions — are event studies, not daily cross-sectional factors; your harness needs both modes)

Then a registry: one row per spec version — hypothesis, frozen spec hash, eval results, number of variants tried. Enforce a variant budget per idea (say ≤5 spec amendments) and apply a deflated-Sharpe or FDR haircut across the batch. With 67 ideas × variants, ~5% of garbage will look great by chance; the registry is your only defense.
Step 4 (new): Close the loop back to ideation
Have Opus write a one-page results memo per idea in a fixed template (what worked, where it failed, data surprises, decay profile). Feed these memos back into the GPT/Fable context for the next ideation round on that region. Right now your loop is open — the ideation model never learns that, e.g., Taiwan branch flow works in mid-caps but dies in the top-50; that's exactly the context that makes round-2 ideas better.
Two orchestration-level suggestions
Sequence by shared infrastructure, not by idea. Many ideas share a data build (KR-1/KR-2 share KRX tape work; CN-1/CN-3 share cninfo filings; EU-1 is one scraper serving 20 registries). Build the dataset once with its data card and PIT tests, then implement the 2–5 signals that sit on it. Your backlog of 67 ideas is really ~25 data-source builds.
Keep ideation and implementation sessions separate even within Opus. The Opus session doing feasibility review should not be the one writing code from the frozen spec — a fresh session receiving only the spec + data cards + harness docs can't inherit unstated assumptions from the negotiation phase, which is a common source of "the code does what we discussed, not what the spec says."
